    <stitle>TSI 92-12-16 - Revised 7.3L Final Fuel Filter/Water Separator Assembly</stitle>
    <tsi id="tsi921216" tsitype="truck">
        <tsinumber>92-12-16</tsinumber>
        <tsidate>November, 1992</tsidate>
        <subjectfile>ENGINE</subjectfile>
        <subjectgroup>
            <subject>Revised 7.3L Final Fuel Filter/Water Separator Assembly</subject>
        </subjectgroup>
        <apply>
            <configure>
                <truckmodelgroup/>

                <truckmodel>4000</truckmodel>
                <engfamgroup/>

                <engfam>7.3L</engfam>
            </configure>
        </apply>
        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <para>This TSI applies to 4000 Series U-Haul applications only.</para>
                <para>The revised final fuel filter/water separator assembly features:</para>
                <seqlist>
                    <item>
                        <para>New (shorter) priming valve.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>New continuous vent valve (Pkg.).</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>New fuel filter element gasket.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>New fuel heater.</para>
                    </item>
                </seqlist>
                <para>The new priming valve functions in the same manner as the old valve. The valve body is shorter in
                    length and its thread size is 1/8-27 NPTF versus the old valve with thread size of 1/16-27 NPTF.
                    Refer to
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9212161">Figure 1</hotlnk>.
                </para>
                <figure id="f9212161" figsize="pg-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9212161.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 1. New Versus Old Final Fuel Filter Water/Separator Assembly</caption>
                </figure>
                <para>The
                    <emph type="bold">new</emph>
                    continuous vent valve (Pkg.) (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9212162">Figure 2</hotlnk>) P/N 1 816 623 C91, consists of:
                </para>
                <seqlist>
                    <item>
                        <para>Valve Body</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Spring</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Nylon Ball</para>
                    </item>
                </seqlist>
                <para>The valve body, spring and nylon ball are supplied separately in this service package versus the
                    old valve which was an integral unit.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>The old vent valve and new vent valve body (fitting) are identical in size and appearance
                            as shown in
                            <hotlnk xrefid="f9212161">Figure 1</hotlnk>
                            and
                            <hotlnk xrefid="f9212162">Figure 2</hotlnk>.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <para>If vent valve removal is required during service, be careful when removing the vent valve body
                    from the fuel filter header. If the valve is the new type, removing the valve body will expose the
                    spring and nylon ball (check valve) as shown in
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9212162">Figure 2</hotlnk>.
                </para>
                <figure id="f9212162" figsize="pg-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9212162.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 2. New And Old Continuous Vent Valve</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>DO NOT INTERMIX the new vent valve with the old vent valve. The depth of the old fuel
                            filter header cavity which houses the old vent valve, is too shallow to accept the new vent
                            valve parts. Substituting the new valve for the old will result in compressing the new
                            valve's spring beyond its design limits and vent valve failure.
                        </para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
                <para>The new fuel filter header service package P/N 1 816 613 C91 contains the new fuel filter header
                    which accommodates the new priming valve and continuous vent valve parts.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>The revised final fuel filter header was revised in two stages. If fuel filter header
                            replacement is necessary during service, use the chart below (
                            <hotlnk xrefid="t9212161">Table 1</hotlnk>) to identify which fuel filter header
                            configuration (old, new stage 1, or 2) is being serviced. Use the new fuel filter header
                            package along with the REQUIRED new parts as shown in the table below.
